1. PUBLIC URL
--------------
https://lekatca1.github.io/cabsonline-part2

(Deploy with: npm run deploy)


2. TECHNOLOGY STACK
--------------------
- React 18.2
- react-leaflet 4.2.1 + Leaflet 1.9.4 (map)
- OpenStreetMap tiles (free, no API key needed)
- localStorage (demo data storage, no backend needed for GitHub Pages)
- gh-pages 6.0 (deployment)
- CSS (plain, no extra libraries)


3. HOW TO RUN LOCALLY
----------------------
Requirements: Node.js 16+, npm

Steps:
  1. Unzip the project folder
  2. Open terminal in the project folder
  3. Run: npm install
  4. Run: npm start
  5. Open http://localhost:3000 in your browser

To build for production:
  npm run build

To deploy to GitHub Pages:
  npm run deploy


4. MICROSERVICE API ENDPOINTS
------------------------------
This application is deployed as a static site on GitHub Pages and therefore
does not call a remote PHP/MySQL backend. Instead, data persistence is handled
via the browser's localStorage API, which serves as a local data layer
replacing the Part 1 PHP/MySQL backend. This approach was chosen because
GitHub Pages does not support server-side execution.

Local Data Operations (localStorage):

  READ    bookings
            localStorage.getItem('bookings')
            Returns all bookings as a JSON array.
            Used by: TrackPage, AdminPage, HistoryPage

  WRITE   bookings
            localStorage.setItem('bookings', JSON.stringify([...all, newBooking]))
            Appends a new booking object to the stored array.
            Used by: BookPage (on successful form submission)

  UPDATE  bookings/{brn}
            localStorage.setItem('bookings', JSON.stringify(updated))
            Maps over the array and updates the status field of the matching
            booking by BRN from 'unassigned' to 'assigned'.
            Used by: AdminPage (on Assign button click)

Remote Endpoints:

  OpenStreetMap Tile Server
    URL:    https://{s}.tile.openstreetmap.org/{z}/{x}/{y}.png
    Method: GET (handled internally by Leaflet)
    Purpose: Renders the interactive map tiles on the Book a Taxi and
             Driver Map views. Free to use, no API key required.


5. FEATURE DESCRIPTIONS
------------------------

Feature 1 - Book a Taxi (tab: "Book a Taxi")
  Extends Part 1 booking.html into a React component.
  - All required fields: cname, phone, unumber, snumber, stname, sbname, dsbname, date, time
  - Client-side validation (required fields, phone format, date not in past)
  - Generates BRN in incremental format BRN00001, BRN00002, etc.
  - Displays a confirmation message with booking reference number, pickup date and time
  - Stores booking in localStorage
  - Leaflet map on the right panel shows nearby mock driver locations in real time

Feature 2 - Booking Status Tracker (tab: "Track Booking")
  Allows customers to check the current status of their booking.
  - Enter a BRN (e.g. BRN00001) to look up a booking
  - Validates BRN format before querying
  - Displays a visual progress bar: unassigned -> assigned -> completed
  - Shows full booking details in a structured table

Feature 3 - Fare Estimator (tab: "Fare Estimator")
  Estimates the fare for a trip before the customer books.
  - Select pickup and destination from a list of Auckland suburbs
  - Enter pickup time to check for night surcharge (10pm-6am = +20%)
  - Calculates base fare ($3.50 flag fall) plus per-kilometre rate ($2.20/km)
  - Displays the estimated total and a typical min/max fare range

Feature 4 - Driver Map View (tab: "Book a Taxi" side panel)
  Shows mock taxi driver locations on an interactive Leaflet map.
  - Uses Leaflet + OpenStreetMap (no API key needed)
  - Green dot markers = online drivers, grey = offline
  - Click any marker to see driver name, car model, plate number, and suburb
  - Filter drivers by online/offline status
  - Driver summary cards displayed below the map


6. TESTING INSTRUCTIONS
------------------------

Example booking flow:
  1. Go to "Book a Taxi" tab
  2. Fill in: Name=John Smith, Phone=0211234567, Street No=1, Street=Queen St
  3. Leave date/time as default (current)
  4. Click "Book Now"
  5. Note your BRN (e.g. BRN00001)

Track a booking:
  1. Go to "Track Booking" tab
  2. Enter BRN00001 (or whatever BRN you received)
  3. Click Search to see details and status progress bar

Fare estimate:
  1. Go to "Fare Estimator" tab
  2. Pick "Auckland CBD" as pickup, "Albany" as destination
  3. Try 23:00 as time to see night surcharge applied
  4. Click "Estimate Fare"

Driver map:
  1. Go to "Book a Taxi" tab and view the map panel on the right
  2. Click on green/grey dot markers to see driver info popups
  3. Use the online/offline filter buttons

Admin:
  1. Go to "Admin" tab
  2. Leave search empty and click "Search Bookings" to see upcoming unassigned bookings
  3. Enter a specific BRN to find a record, then click "Assign"

History:
  1. Go to "History" tab to see all bookings made this session
  2. Use the filter pills to view by status

Sample driver IDs: D001, D002, D003, D004, D005, D006


7. LIMITATIONS / KNOWN ISSUES
-------------------------------
- Data is stored in localStorage only — it resets if the browser clears storage
  or the user opens the app in a different browser/device
- Fare estimates are approximate (based on fixed suburb distances, not real GPS routing)
- Driver locations are simulated mock data, not real-time GPS
- No authentication — same as Part 1 (not required by the assignment specification)
- The "assigned" and "completed" status can only be updated via the Admin tab;
  customers cannot change their own booking status (intentional design decision)
- BRN numbering is based on the length of the localStorage array, so if bookings
  are cleared mid-session, BRN numbers may repeat


7. REFLECTION ON AI-SUPPORTED DEVELOPMENT
-------------------------------------------
AI assistance (Claude) was used to help scaffold the React component structure,
suggest appropriate Leaflet setup for fixing default marker icons in React,
and advise on how to structure localStorage as a demo replacement for a PHP backend
on GitHub Pages. The core logic (validation rules, BRN format, field names) was
taken directly from the Part 1 specification and existing code to ensure consistency.

The student was responsible for all design decisions including feature selection,
UX layout, field validation rules, fare calculation logic, and ensuring the BRN
format and field naming conventions matched the Part 1 specification exactly.
AI was used as a productivity tool, not as a replacement for understanding.
